ro’s is a brand that’s entirely devoted to crafting great bike tools. Their tire levers, which come in vibrant shades of neon pink, green, yellow, and orange, clip together and will never get lost in your saddlebag, and will never let you down.</p><p>The plastic is burly, and while they’re not the fanciest in terms of grip or style, they simply do the job.</p><ul><li>Color: <a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/dp/B001SN8IW0/?tag=20br-20\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Pink</a>, <a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/dp/B001SN8IW0/?tag=20br-20\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Green</a>, <a href=\"https://www.avantlink.com/click.php?tt=el&amp;merchant_id=e295c418-295a-447c-b265-734e25f82503&amp;website_id=3407ca35-0b50-44fe-aeb1-9ab6a93bba54&amp;url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.rei.com%2Fproduct%2F705651%2Fpedros-tire-levers\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Yellow</a>, <a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/dp/B000N22G16/?tag=20br-20\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Orange</a></li><li>Dimensions: 130mm length, 87 grams</li><li>Price: $5.25</li></ul><h3><span>&nbsp;<strong>TOUGHEST TIRE LEVERS:</strong>&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/dp/B07L9GS8ST/?tag=20br-20\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Snēk Cycling Lifeboat Levers</a>&nbsp;</span></h3><p><a href=\"https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/20190947/snek-cycling-lifeboat-tire-lever-valve-core-remover.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/20190947/snek-cycling-lifeboat-tire-lever-valve-core-remover.jpg\" alt=\"snek cycling tire lever with metal insert and integrated valve core remover and bottle opener\" width=\"682\" height=\"355\" data-ezsrcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/20190947/snek-cycling-lifeboat-tire-lever-valve-core-remover.jpg 682w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/20190947/snek-cycling-lifeboat-tire-lever-valve-core-remover-297x155.jpg 297w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/20190947/snek-cycling-lifeboat-tire-lever-valve-core-remover-120x62.jpg 120w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 682px) 100vw, 682px\" ezimgfmt=\"rs rscb26 src ng ngcb26 srcset\" data-ezsrc=\"https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/20190947/snek-cycling-lifeboat-tire-lever-valve-core-remover.jpg\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/20190947/snek-cycling-lifeboat-tire-lever-valve-core-remover.jpg 682w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/20190947/snek-cycling-lifeboat-tire-lever-valve-core-remover-297x155.jpg 297w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/20190947/snek-cycling-lifeboat-tire-lever-valve-core-remover-120x62.jpg 120w\"></a></p><p>For those tires that just won’t come off, there’s the Snēk Cycling Lifeboat Levers, which sandwich a full-length metal insert inside the plastic outer shell. Even though most of the plastic levers here are unlikely to bend, these take it a step further.</p><p>They incorporate valve core removers into the design, rotated 90º from each other on either end. And they swap the typical spoke hook on the opposite end for a bottle opener. Nice.</p><p>The Lifeboat levers come in black, olive green, or light blue. The extra construction and materials makes them our most expensive recommendation, but sometimes it’s worth a few extra bucks to get the job done. Plus, you’re supporting a small business that makes them in the USA and guarantees them for life.</p><ul><li>Color: black, light blue, olive green</li><li>Dimensions: 120mm length, 48 grams</li><li>Price: $20</li></ul><h2>Frequently Asked Questions About Tire Levers</h2><p><strong>Do I need tire levers?<br></strong>Technically, no, but probably yes…at least at some point. Tire levers will make a flat change a lot smoother, since they help you quickly remove your tire from the rim. And they avoid getting your hands greasy or dirt-covered in the process.</p><p>They also can save your rim. If you don’t have tire levers, you may need to resort to using something that could damage your rim in your attempt to detach your tire. So, if you value your rim and your fingers, carry a set in your saddlebag at all times. (Looking for a good multitool to go with your tire levers? We have a list of <a href=\"https://bikerumor.com/2021/06/25/best-bike-multitools-minitools/\">our favorite bike multitools right here</a>.)</p><figure id=\"attachment_265662\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-265662\"><a href=\"https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/17081949/pedros-tire-levers-2.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/17081949/pedros-tire-levers-2.jpg\" alt=\"pedros tire levers\" width=\"1600\" height=\"1200\" data-ezsrcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/17081949/pedros-tire-levers-2.jpg 1600w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/17081949/pedros-tire-levers-2-297x223.jpg 297w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/17081949/pedros-tire-levers-2-800x600.jpg 800w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/17081949/pedros-tire-levers-2-120x90.jpg 120w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/17081949/pedros-tire-levers-2-768x576.jpg 768w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/17081949/pedros-tire-levers-2-1536x1152.jpg 1536w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/17081949/pedros-tire-levers-2-696x522.jpg 696w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/17081949/pedros-tire-levers-2-1068x801.jpg 1068w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/17081949/pedros-tire-levers-2-560x420.jpg 560w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/17081949/pedros-tire-levers-2-80x60.jpg 80w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/17081949/pedros-tire-levers-2-265x198.jpg 265w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1600px) 100vw, 1600px\" ezimgfmt=\"rs rscb26 src ng ngcb26 srcset\" data-ezsrc=\"https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/17081949/pedros-tire-levers-2.jpg\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/17081949/pedros-tire-levers-2.jpg 1600w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/17081949/pedros-tire-levers-2-297x223.jpg 297w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/17081949/pedros-tire-levers-2-800x600.jpg 800w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/17081949/pedros-tire-levers-2-120x90.jpg 120w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/17081949/pedros-tire-levers-2-768x576.jpg 768w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/17081949/pedros-tire-levers-2-1536x1152.jpg 1536w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/17081949/pedros-tire-levers-2-696x522.jpg 696w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/17081949/pedros-tire-levers-2-1068x801.jpg 1068w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/17081949/pedros-tire-levers-2-560x420.jpg 560w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/17081949/pedros-tire-levers-2-80x60.jpg 80w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/17081949/pedros-tire-levers-2-265x198.jpg 265w\"></a><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-265662\">Tire levers can also be used to help seat tubeless tires. Run the tire lever around the rim, guiding the tire into place on the rim and allowing the sealant to spread out.</figcaption></figure><p><strong>How do you use tire levers?<br></strong>Tire levers help you to pry your tire off by sliding under the bead of the tire, then gently bringing that bead over and off of the rim of the wheel. Once you have one lever under the tire bead, you simply press it back to create space, then use the hook at the end of the lever to fasten it to a spoke.</p><p>Then, use your second lever to slide into the space created by the first lever, and work the second lever around the rim, fully detaching the tire so that you can pull out the tube and replace it. You can also reverse the process to get the tire back onto the rim of the wheel, and to carefully make sure that no bits of the tube are caught under the bead of the tire, since that can lead to a pinch flat.</p><p><span><iframe loading=\"lazy\" width=\"696\" height=\"392\" data-ezsrc=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/IbLns_P0khA?version=3&amp;rel=1&amp;showsearch=0&amp;showinfo=1&amp;iv_load_policy=1&amp;fs=1&amp;hl=en-US&amp;autohide=2&amp;wmode=transparent\" allowfullscreen=\"true\" sandbox=\"allow-scripts allow-same-origin allow-popups allow-presentation\"></iframe></span></p><p><strong>Can you use a multitool as a tire lever?</strong><br>While you can technically most sharp, hard objects as tire levers, we highly recommend not using anything other than an actual tire lever or your bare hands. That’s because using metal (like a small Allen key or screwdriver from your multitool) could scrape or damage your tire’s rim, and potentially further puncture or stress the tube or tire. It could also puncture or scratch the rim tape, which will ruin a tubeless setup. That said, if it’s between walking your bike 10 miles home or using a multitool to pry off a tire, we’re not judging you.</p><p><strong>Can you use your hands instead of tire levers?</strong><br>Sometimes, yes, but it takes a lot of hand strength and a bit of know-how. Most tires are tight enough to the rim that they won’t come right off (and if they do, that might be part of the reason for your flat). But you can use your hands to work your way around the tire, pulling the rubber as taunt as possible by getting the beads into the center channel to allow a bit of give in a single spot, allowing you to peel the tire off the rim.</p><p><strong>Do you really need to carry two tire levers?</strong><br>Two will get the job done faster, but you can <em>usually</em> manage with just one, if you’re really tight on space or trying to save a few extra grams of weight.</p><p><strong>Why does tire lever quality matter?</strong><br>Some of the cheaper tire levers have the tendency to bend and snap (and not in a fun Legally Blonde kind of way) at the worst possible moment. And metal ones can damage or bend your rims, so we don’t recommend those. A good set of tire levers—like the ones we’ve recommended above—will usually last you a lifetime.</p></div></div>","author":"Molly Hurford","siteTitle":"Bikerumor","siteHash":"49f427af0a926f4232eb837006841d7242e153e3afbb590f32e4b104ea3e2718","entryHash":"046ca484ed3c7282af88f3eadee67e1ce183bab5ff16c4f4c6c53a0281826c59","category":"Cycling"}